\begin_layout Subsubsection
Partial fill
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common discharge problem occurs at the pulse coupling capacitors
 as these are most difficult to clean.
 Potting only the pulse coupling capacitors is usually effective and can
 be done after the fitler is epoxied together without risk of adding problematic
 air voids.
 This procedure is based on the deaeration procedure specified in the RTV11
 technical data sheet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Place a filter that has been epoxied together in a jig so it stands connector
 end up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mix RTV11 with the minimum amount of catalyst to maximize the working time
 for degassing and minimizing voids.
 For the DBT catalyst included with the RTV11 0.1% catalyst was used by adding
 one drop to 20 grams of RTV11.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use a syringe and 16 gauge needle to inject 2 mL of potting compound through
 the fill port by the pulse PCB end of the filter.
 This will fill the filter to about half way between the fill port and the
 top of the pulse coupling capacitors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Place the filter on jig in a vacuum degassing chamber along with any remaining
 mixed potting compound in a separate open container so any frothing that
 occurs can be observed in the remaining potting compound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw a vacuum of 33 mBar to degass the potting compound, leaving the compound
 under vacuum for at least 2 minutes after frothing ceases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Complete fill
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A complete fill is best performed on a filter where the endcap and pulse
 PCB are attached to the filter with epoxy only around the edge of a slotted
 pulse PCB, this allows air to easily escape while potting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Place a filter that has been epoxied together in a jig so it stands connector
 end down.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mix RTV11 with the minimum amount of catalyst to maximize the working time
 for degassing and minimizing voids.
 For the DBT catalyst included with the RTV11 0.1% catalyst was used by adding
 one drop to 20 grams of RTV11.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use a syringe and 16 gauge needle to inject 3.5 mL of potting compound through
 the fill port by the SHV connector end of the filter.
 Do not draw more potting compund into the syringe than necessary as it
 needs to be left in the mixing container to be degassed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Place the filter on jig in a vacuum degassing chamber along with any remaining
 mixed potting compound so any frothing that occurs can be observed in the
 remaining potting compound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw a vacuum of 33 mBar to degass the potting compound, leaving the compound
 under vacuum for at least 2 minutes after frothing ceases.
 There is an air void in the SHV connector between the input resistor and
 connector body, this step is also to fill this void.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Filling the rest of the filter depends on if air can escape out the end
 cap.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If the pulse PCB is slotted and air can escape out the end cap then fill
 the filter the rest of the way through the SHV connector end fill port
 until potting compound comes to the top of the hole in the end cap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Seal the fill port by the end cap with an M2 bolt and leave the port near
 the SHV connector open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Seal the fill port with an M2 nut and keep the filter oriented connector
 end down as the potting compound cures.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If the endcap is sealed and air can only escape out the fill port.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Fill with an additional 10 mL of compound, this puts the level of the potting
 compound at about the guard ring and ensures the void between the resistor
 and SHV connector is filled while continuing to fill the filter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Seal the fill port by the SHV connector with an M2 bolt and tilt the fitler
 on it's side so the end cap side fill port is up.
 Continue to fill through the end cap end fill port to the maximum extend
 possible.
 Keep adding more potting compound as it settles and the air void shifts
 to the side with the fill port.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Seal the fill port and tilt the filter so the SHV connector end is elevated
 at a 30 degree angle with the connector end fill port down.
 There is a slot in the guard ring on the fill port side and this will keep
 an air void remaining from easily moving past the guard ring.
 Any air voids along the tube wall by the guard ring will be in a region
 of minimal electric field.
 Any air void on the SHV connector side of the guard ring will move to the
 space between the SHV connector body and the tube, which is another region
 of low electric field.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
